  <!-- DON'T FAIL -->
  <div class="dontfail">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">§ 04 — Don't get tripped</div>
      <h2>Things that quietly <em>fail you</em>.</h2>
      <div class="section-sub">Six small process slips that the orientation flags as automatic disqualifiers. Re-read before each upload.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="fail-list">
      <div class="item">
        <div class="num">01</div>
        <h5>Certificate without your name</h5>
        <p>Coursera certificates must show your enrolled name. Anonymous downloads or screenshots aren't accepted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="item">
        <div class="num">02</div>
        <h5>Skipping any single submission</h5>
        <p>All steps are mandatory. Miss one, the whole capstone is recorded as Fail — even if everything else scored full marks.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="item">
        <div class="num">03</div>
        <h5>Recording video outside the LMS</h5>
        <p>Both reflection videos must be recorded in the LMS itself. Phone, Zoom or screen-recorder uploads won't be evaluated.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="item">
        <div class="num">04</div>
        <h5>Audio or text in place of video</h5>
        <p>"Reflection video" is taken literally. Audio files, written notes or slide decks instead of a video won't count.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="item">
        <div class="num">05</div>
        <h5>Using a relative as your EPG</h5>
        <p>Spouse, blood relatives and direct relatives are explicitly disallowed — even if their qualifications check out on paper.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="item">
        <div class="num">06</div>
        <h5>Editing a downloaded certificate</h5>
        <p>Any edit to a Coursera certificate — even fixing the name — is treated as fraud. Result: Fail for the entire course.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
